[2] Canada
Date: Sat, 19 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canadian Press via Toronto Star, 18 Jun 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thestar.com/NASApp/cs/ContentServer?pagename=thestar/Layout/Article_Type1&c=Article&cid=1087552989752&call_pageid=968332188774&col=968350116467>

Mad cow hammering farm incomes: StatsCan
-----------------------------------------
Twice as many cattle-producing families live on less than CAD 20 000 [USD
14 671] a year as a result of the mad cow crisis, says Statistics Canada.
The new figures, released today, also show the U.S. border closure in May
2003 has sliced the income of all ranchers by an average of 1/3.
Total losses to the industry since one cow with bovine spongiform
encephalopathy, or BSE, was discovered in Alberta during 2003 have been
estimated at nearly $3 billion [USD 2.2 billion], but that sheds little
light on how the crisis has affected people, said Verna Mitura of
Statistics Canada.
"What we wanted to try to do was take this $3-billion number and say, 'How
does that relate when you're talking about individual farm families?' " she
said from Ottawa.
The losses vary according to the size of the farm. Canada's 2200 largest
cattle farms, which have more than $500 000 [USD 366 784] in receipts, lost
an average of $220 000 [USD 161 385] each due to the crisis.
A more typical cattle farm, with about 150 animals and at least $100 000
[USD 73 356] in farm income, lost about $20 000 [USD 14 671]. That cut
income from about $60 000 [USD 44 014] -- which is Canada's average family
income -- down to about $40,000 [USD 29 342].
On the low end, nearly twice as many cattle farm families are now living on
less than $20 000 [USD 14 671] a year.
In 2002, there were 6800 families in that category -- about 14 percent of
the total. After a year of BSE, that total had risen to an estimated 13 400
-- about 27 percent of cattle farm families.
Fewer than 7 percent of families in the general Canadian population live on
that low an income, says Statistics Canada. The study only included
unincorporated farms.
Mad cow disease stopped the flow of Canadian beef to the United States
almost immediately after a northern Alberta cow was found to be sick in May
2003. The border has since reopened to most cuts of processed beef but
remains closed to shipments of live cattle.
Speaking in Kamloops, B.C., federal Agriculture Minister Bob Speller
suggested the border could fully reopen by 1 Sep 2004.
"We are getting assurances from the United States that they are well
underway in their process," he said. "It should be resolved by Sept 1st."
--
