[3] United States - testing
Date: Sat, 19 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press via The Wichita Eagle, 19 Jun 2004 [edited]
<http://www.kansas.com/mld/eagle/business/industries/agriculture/8960480.htm>

USDA steps up mad-cow testing -- slowly
---------------------------------------
Early screening of high-risk cattle for mad cow disease has found no
suspected cases in the 2871 tests performed in the expanded program's first
2 weeks.
But the U.S. Department of Agriculture's USD 70 million testing program has
been slow to gear up to the point where it can screen 220 000 animals for
bovine spongiform encephalopathy in the next 12 to 18 months.
The program, which started 1 Jun 2004, is meant to reassure domestic and
international consumers that U.S. beef is safe to eat.
People can get a variation of the brain-wasting Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease
by eating infected beef.
Most of the agency's 12 mad cow testing laboratories nationwide, including
the one at Kansas State University, still aren't operating. States such as
Kansas have been bogged down in contract negotiations with rendering plants
in the effort to get brain samples for testing.
"Technically, it started 1 Jun 2004, but we haven't received the OK from
the USDA for our specific program and how we are going to run it," said
Kansas Animal Health Commissioner George Teagarden. "Until that gets
approved, we are in a slowdown mode."
But USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service said that the
infrastructure for the expanded testing program was in place 1 Jun 2004 and
that the agency is just now ironing out details.
"On the first day, it wasn't expected we would be performing at maximum
output," said spokesman Jim Rogers.
Kansas -- the nation's 2nd-largest beef producer -- during 2003 tested 150
animals for BSE. It is supposed to test 7000 animals under the expanded
program, but the final figure is likely to be closer to 5000 because
livestock in the state's northern counties will go to Nebraska for testing,
Teagarden said.
"There is no question in my mind we are doing as much as we can right now
-- and we will be doing more," Teagarden said.
Kevin Varner, the Health Inspection Service veterinarian in charge of the
Kansas BSE-testing program, said 47 Kansas animals have been tested (most
of them out of state) since the expanded program began.
Kansas and Nebraska, among other states, are having contract troubles with
rendering companies, he said. To get the brain samples it needs to test,
the Health Inspection Service reimburses the companies for holding and
identifying carcasses.
"They want more than we want to pay," Varner said. "We have taxpayer
dollars we have to watch."
Most of the regional testing laboratories approved to date are still not
operating. A few have had equipment and contracting issues. All are
expected to be on line within weeks, Rogers said.
The agency's own testing laboratory in Iowa is running, Rogers said, as are
the new regional laboratories in Georgia, Washington, California, Colorado
and Texas.
Kansas State University has one of the 5 laboratories approved 11 May 2004
by the Health Inspection Service. 7 other labs were approved in March.
George Kennedy, director of the Kansas State's veterinary diagnostic
laboratory, said it will be July before its BSE lab is running.
After some initial juggling to find a room, the university is now working
to get the physical laboratory prepared -- trying to get tables and
electrical outlets for the computers, for example. Next week they plan to
start training staff.
Meanwhile, the nation's meat industry is nervously watching USDA's initial
BSE testing results, which are posted on its Health Inspection Service Web
site.
<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/lpa/issues/bse-enhan_surv/bse_test_results.html>
The department created an uproar in the cattle industry when it disclosed
it planned to make public all the preliminary test results -- including any
BSE-positive results from the less accurate rapid tests -- before
conducting more extensive and time-consuming tests on suspect samples.
"It is somewhat dangerous to do that, but it is also dangerous to keep that
quiet," Teagarden said. "We know things leak out. I think an official
announcement is better than a rumor. With this enhanced program there will
be rumors if we are not very open."
The Health Inspection Service during 2003 tested 20 543 animals, most of
them downer cattle that could not stand or walk.
After the nation's first mad cow case in December 2003, the agency doubled
the number to 40 000. It later expanded the number to 220 000 high-risk
animals in a move to reassure foreign governments. [For comparative testing
figures of risk animals in the EU, see further in item 4. - Mod.AS]
Some 35 million cattle are slaughtered each year in the United States.
[Byline: Roxana Hegeman]
--
